Imagine you go to a busy fast-food restaurant and order a burger. The cashier takes your money and hands you a buzzer with an order number. That buzzer is the Promise.
You don’t have your burger yet, but you have a “promise” that you will get it eventually. Because you aren’t forced to stand at the register waiting, you can go sit down, check your phone, or chat with a friend (this is non-blocking behavior).
Your Promise (the buzzer) can be in one of three states (Remember this for interview, Promises have 3 states):

• Pending: You are still waiting for the food.

• Resolved (Fulfilled): The buzzer flashes! Your food is ready and you get your burger.

• Rejected: The cashier comes over and says they are completely out of beef. You don’t get your burger, and you get an error instead.
How the Guard (Node.js) Handles the Buzzer
To connect this back to our earlier security Hostel Warden analogy, Node.js manages these resolved Promises using high-priority queues that sit entirely outside of the standard event loop rooms (phases).
Please read NodeJS Event Loop first if you are feeling lost.
When a Promise is resolved, its callback is placed into the Promise microtask queue (the “hallway”). The engine checks and completely drains this microtask queue immediately after finishing its current operation, before it is permitted to move on to the next phase of the event loop.
However, your Promise buzzer isn’t the absolute highest priority. If the guard gets a call on his walkie-talkie (a process.nextTick() task), the execution sequence guarantees that the engine will drain the entire process.nextTick() queue before it processes any Promise microtasks.
A Critical “Gotcha”
When I am writing code with Promises, I usually always prepare for the “Rejected” scenario.
One of the most common ways developers accidentally crash their applications is by creating “Forgotten Promises”, which is a code pattern that leads to severe memory leaks. If you execute a Promise but fail to handle the rejection scenario (for example, by forgetting to attach a .catch(console.error) block), that rejected Promise can linger in your application's memory indefinitely. Always handle your errors so your Promises don't get forgotten!
Hands on Time
This section is only effective if you do it in an editor. Open a code editor. I use Programmiz.io
1. The Basic Concept (The Ice Cream Promise)
A Promise represents a value that will exist in the future.
const buyIce Cream = new Promise((resolve, reject) => {
let shopOpen = true; // Change to false to test the error path
if (shopOpen) {
resolve("🍦 Got the ice cream!");
} else {
reject("😢 Shop is closed.");
}
});// How to use it:
buyIceCream
.then((result) => console.log(result)) // Runs if resolve() is called
.catch((error) => console.error(error)); // Runs if reject() is called2. Simulating Asynchronous Delay (setTimeout)
Promises handle tasks that take time, like waiting for a database or a timer.
const waitTwoSeconds = () => {
return new Promise((resolve) => {
setTimeout(() => {
resolve("⏰ 2 seconds have passed!");
}, 2000);
});
};// How to use it:
console.log("Start waiting...");
waitTwoSeconds().then((message) => console.log(message));3. Real-World API Fetch (With Error Handling)
The following code is how we fetch network data and handle HTTP errors properly, as fetch only rejects on network failures. Try with different free apis. Play around
const fetchUserData = (userId) => {
return fetch(`https://typicode.com{userId}`)
.then((response) => {
// Always check if the HTTP response status is okay
if (!response.isOk) {
throw new Error(`User not found (Status: ${response.status})`);
}
return response.json(); // Converts response to a JavaScript object
});
};// How to use it:
fetchUserData(1)
.then((user) => console.log(`User Name: ${user.name}`))
.catch((error) => console.error(`Error fetching data: ${error.message}`));4. Modernizing with async/await
Now that we understand .then() and .catch(), let’s work withasync/await as cleaner, more readable syntax for handling Promises.
const showUserDashboard = async () => {
try {
console.log("Loading dashboard..."); // The 'await' keyword pauses execution until the promise settles
const user = await fetchUserData(1);
console.log(`Success! Welcome back, ${user.name}.`);
} catch (error) {
// Captures errors from fetchUserData or any other step inside try
console.error(`Dashboard error: ${error.message}`);
}
};
// How to use
showUserDashboard();Do it hands on. Suggest how we can improve this. Keep learning, keep growing
